04737nam a22006495i 9780822382256DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t19941994ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223822567 a10.1515/97808223822562doi  a(DE-B1597)553826  a(OCoLC)1136418674  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPR535.L7bE88 1994 7aLIT0140002bisacsh04a811/.3093542201 aEstrin, Barbara L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLaura :bUncovering Gender and Genre in Wyatt, Donne and Marvell /cBarbara L. Estrin; Stanley Fish, Fredric Jameson. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1994] 4c©1994  a1 online resource (360 p.) :b3 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPost-Contemporary Interventions00tFrontmatter -- tPermission to quote from the following is gratefully acknowledged -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on Editions -- tIntroduction: Gender Performance and Genre Slippage -- tPETRARCH -- tWYATT -- tDONNE -- tMARVELL -- tMusing Afterward -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow do men imagine women? In the poetry of Petrarch and his English successors-Wyatt, Donne, and Marvell-the male poet persistently imagines pursuing a woman, Laura, whom he pursues even as she continues to deny his affections. Critics have long held that, in objectifying Laura, these male-authored texts deny the imaginative, intellectual, and physical life of the woman they idealize. In Laura, Barbara L. Estrin counters this traditional view by focusing not on the generative powers of the male poet, but on the subjectivity of the imagined woman and the imaginative space of the poems she occupies.Through close readings of the Rime sparse and the works of Wyatt, Donne, and Marvell, Estrin uncovers three Lauras: Laura-Daphne, who denies sexuality; Laura-Eve, who returns the poet's love; and Laura-Mercury, who reinvents her own life. Estrin claims that in these three guises Laura subverts both genre and gender, thereby introducing multiple desires into the many layers of the poems. Drawing upon genre and gender theories advanced by Jean-François Lyotard and Judith Butler to situate female desire in the poem's framework, Estrin shows how genre and gender in the Petrarchan tradition work together to undermine the stability of these very concepts.Estrin's Laura constitutes a fundamental reconceptualization of the Petrarchan tradition and contributes greatly to the postmodern reassessment of the Renaissance period. In its descriptions of how early modern poets formulate questions about sexuality, society and poetry, Laura will appeal to scholars of the English and Italian Renaissance, of gender studies, and of literary criticism and theory generally.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aEnglish poetryxItalian influences. 0aEnglish poetryyEarly modern, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 0aLiterary formxHistoryy16th century. 0aLiterary formxHistoryy17th century. 0aLove poetry, EnglishxMale authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aSex role in literature. 0aWomen and literaturezEnglandxHistoryy16th century. 0aWomen and literaturezEnglandxHistoryy17th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Poetry.2bisacsh1 aFish, Stanley, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJameson, Fredric, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999z978311071360240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822382256zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822382256423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822382256.jpg  a978-3-11-071360-2  DUK Archive eBook-